<font color="#FF0000">WITHOUT A WING AND A PRAYER </font><br>
<tt>Sat Jun 28 16:19:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear wingman:<br><br>
There is nothing painful about your story, more then likely I was the one firing at the villagers out in the open rice paddies.<br>
Shortly after I returned from Chu Lai where I had been medivacked. I rejoined my company at An Hoa. As evening began to fall we went out to relieve the out posts by the perimeter wire. We all knew and the villagers knew that at curfew they were out of the field or considered individuals using the time to pinpoint where or what bunkers Marines would be standing watch that night. Many times we captured so called villagers out past curfew near where they had placed aiming sticks so that the NVA would be able to zero in on the bunkers where Marines would be that evening. Hill 65, 10, 52 all were overrun because some weak-minded soldier or lame Lt. felt that we should wait a few hours or give them a few minutes more this caused the lives of Marines and it was totally unnecessary. <br>
The villagers (those that were genuine villagers) knew when to come in and out of their fields. The water buffaloes knew and as soon as the shadows of darkness about 5:30 began to fall they were on their way in. It probably wasn't me that shot that day however, I carried an M-60 machine gun. The times I opened fire like that, the first rounds were over their head if they did not dede mou (take off) I would not hesitate to open fire. <br>
I remember the first time I did that, my lt. coming over one day wanting to know why I had opened up near the farmers who were out in the. He was new, did not last long, got many Marines killed or wounded. <br>
The local villagers never gave us any problems especially those to whom we provided foods, clothing and medical supplies to in the Cac units where we lived among them, ate with them, protected them from the North Vietnamese Communist. It was always the NVA disguised as the farmer that stayed out late. <br><br>
In June of last year, I found the diary I had kept in Vietnam. Listed were the dates and names of the military operations our unit had participated in and the names or nicknames of those that served with us. Some of the names were written down, others emerged from in between the lines. <br><br>
With the names came memories of pain and sorrow, fear and anger, vengeance and compassion. Just as often, I found moments of joy, of laughter and trust, friendship, honor and glory. The diary also made me realize how proud I have been all these years to have served with so many Marines worthy of great honor. <br><br>
I decided to re-write the diary into book form and began to search for supporting information and to attempt to find the Marines that I had served with in India Company, especially those from 1st platoon. It wasn't long before 28 had been found and I had also spoken to many more from 2nd and 3rd platoons. Amazingly, I found that same feeling of pride and honor residing in others as well.  We share a patriotic pride and belief in America that can only be understood by those who have known and have shared the dangers of war and fear. Who have fought against battle-savvy North vitnamese regulars to save the life of local villiagers or a fellow Marine. <br>
Unfortunately, when we returned home we were denied the right to share those precious memories with our loved ones and so for the most part many of us remained silent. Our Patriotic pride fell under the shadow of ill-conceived shame, lies and deception. Ironically, today as we begin to crawl out from behind those rice paddy dikes, our country is also beginning to re-examine what we accomplished in South East Asia. America is beginning to recognize and to honor those that served in the Vietnam War. Now, thirty years later, its time for us to emerge from where we have been pinned down all these years and be proud of what we accomplished. <br><br>
Part of a letter from another Marine I received when I begin to look for Marines that I had served with in Vietnam is included below. He captures what is in the heart and mind of those that served with honor in Vietnam. When we were there 1967-1968, the demonstrators and the drug used was not part of our life we went there to fight an enemy and that is what we did proudly. Today Vietnam hungers for trade and is in desperate need of help, because what the communist promised never materilized. Today they want the economic benefits of a democratic world but are unwilling to give its people who will soon have their own revolution the freedom they crave.<br><br>
&quot;Many in our country questioned and de-based our actions and the war that we fought but could not comprehend that freedom and liberty is non-selective, and resides only in those who fight for it, and then cherish it. The society that I see today is consumed with self-preference, greed and the desire to serve only the self. But buried in this society are the seeds of success for future generations, that being the children of all the servicemen who fought and died in Viet Nam and all other wars. These children have the traits of their fathers, passed on by us, and will certainly bloom and change our country. If it ever becomes necessary to protect our country in the ultimate battle, I feel confident that a group of Marines that I know personally, although gray and older, will move to the front, reassure the unknowing, space ourselves properly and move out!&quot;<br><br>

<p><code>-- Cookbarela@iname.com  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


